g.desc: Hide complex data structures from clients
g.text: Hide complex data structures from clients

g.title: Folded Corner.205
g.desc: The Iterator pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Pr...

g.text: The Iterator pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Principle. The Iterators are separated from the Aggregates (=collections, trees, etc). This enables Iterators and Aggregates to evolve independently. This results in reusability, readability and stability. Reusability, because an Iterator can be reused across multiple Aggregates. Readability, because Iterator logic is separated from Aggregate logic. I.e.: given: Iterator logic resides inside the Aggregate logic and multiple Iterators are applicable to the same Aggregate, then: the Aggregate implementation would be obscured by the Iterator logic. Stability, because the chance of breaking existing Iteration or Aggregate logic becomes smaller.

g.title: Rectangle.210
g.desc: The same traversal logic applies to different aggregates
g.text: The same traversal logic applies to different aggregates

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: The Iterator pattern enables sharing the same traversal logic...

g.text: The Iterator pattern enables sharing the same traversal logic amongst different aggregates. The traversal logic is not bounded to an Aggregate directly, but instead encapsulated in a different object. The transversal logic, encapsulated by the Iterator object, can work with different Aggregates via templating or an abstraction (Polymorphic Iterator).

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Iterator pattern can violate the Single Responsibility Pr...

g.text: The Iterator pattern can violate the Single Responsibility Principle. The Iterator logic shouldn’t be separated from the Aggregate in case there is no need to hide complex data structures, share traversal implementation or have multiple parallel traversals on the same Aggregate. The disadvantage of separating Iterator and Aggregate logic is that the code becomes more scattered. This will make it harder to see the whole, resulting in a decrease in readability. The Iterator can be seen as a form of indirection to the Aggregate, making debugging and navigating more difficult. ‘Merging’ Iterator and Aggregate logic can still comply to Single Responsibility, because both operate on the same (internal) state.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The responsibility of the Iterator is to traverse a certain c...

g.text: The responsibility of the Iterator is to traverse a certain collection, tree or set. The Iterator holds the state (e.g. position) in the traversal, is able to retrieve the item on a position and holds information about the begin and end of the Aggregate. An iterator can have different ‘forms’. E.g. depth first iterator or breath first Iterator. The responsibility of the Aggregate (collection, set or tree) is to swap, add and remove items. The Iterator pattern hides ‘complex’ data structures from the client, by encapsulating the collection and providing a limited (Iteration) interface. This enables data security and client convenience. Data security, because the client does not work with the collection directly, preventing unexpected or accidental data manipulation. Convenience, because the interface is small. This enables easier understandable and mockable code.

g.title: Rectangle.238
g.desc: Apply multiple parallel traversals on the same aggregate object
g.text: Apply multiple parallel traversals on the same aggregate object

g.title: Folded Corner.251
g.desc: The Iterator logic is separated from the Aggregate logic. Thi...

g.text: The Iterator logic is separated from the Aggregate logic. This enables multiple parallel traversals on the same Aggregate. This is possible, because each Iterator is a self-contained object, ‘holding’ its own state (=position). In contrast, not separating the Iterator logic into a separate class, but merging it into the Aggregate, means we do not have the possibility to keep track of two or more different traversal states on the same Aggregate.

g.title: Folded Corner.258
g.desc: The Iterator pattern compliments the Interface Segregation Pr...

g.text: The Iterator pattern compliments the Interface Segregation Principle. The possibility to inject Iterators into client, instead of the ‘whole’ Aggregate (=collection, tree, etc), ensures that clients are not dependent on functions they do not use. This results in stability and maintainability. Stability, because interface changes in the Aggregate don’t impact the test mocks of the client code. Additionally, the clients are dependent on a ‘role-interface’ that prevents unexpected Aggregate changes (=bug reduction). Maintainability, because less recompilation is required in case an interface change is introduced. On top of that, the search hits on the Aggregate interface usage becomes smaller, resulting in more confidence when changing an interface.

g.title: Folded Corner.261
g.desc: The Iterator pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. T...

g.text: The Iterator pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. The Iterators and Aggregates are behind an abstraction. This results in stability and reusability. Stability, because the abstraction enables clients to use ‘new’ concrete Iterators in places where ‘old’ Iterators are used. I.e. the client can change behavior without modification. Reusability, because different Aggregates can re-use the same Iterators, because the Iterators are dependent on an abstract Aggregate.
